@startuml Circular Money Flow Pattern
title Circular Money Flow - Money Laundering Pattern

' This diagram shows how money circulates through multiple accounts
' and returns to the origin, indicating money laundering layering

skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam defaultFontSize 12

package "Circular Money Flow Pattern" {
    rectangle "Account A\n(Criminal)\nInitial: $10,000" as AccountA #FFE6E6
    rectangle "Account B\n(Mule 1)\nReceives: $10,000\nForwards: $9,500" as AccountB #FFF4E6
    rectangle "Account C\n(Mule 2)\nReceives: $9,500\nForwards: $9,000" as AccountC #E6F3FF
    rectangle "Account D\n(Mule 3)\nReceives: $9,000\nReturns: $8,500" as AccountD #E6FFE6
    
    AccountA --> AccountB : "Txn1: $10,000\nRound 1\nDEBITED_FROM"
    AccountB --> AccountC : "Txn2: $9,500\nRound 1\nDEBITED_FROM"
    AccountC --> AccountD : "Txn3: $9,000\nRound 1\nDEBITED_FROM"
    AccountD --> AccountA : "Txn4: $8,500\nRound 1\nCREDITED_TO"
    
    note right of AccountA
        **Pattern Characteristics:**
        - Money flows in a circle
        - Amount decreases each hop
        - Multiple rounds possible
        - Short timeframes (hours/days)
        - High fraud score
    end note
}

legend right
    |= Color |= Meaning |
    | <#FFE6E6> | Source Account (Criminal) |
    | <#FFF4E6> | Intermediate Account (Mule 1) |
    | <#E6F3FF> | Intermediate Account (Mule 2) |
    | <#E6FFE6> | Intermediate Account (Mule 3) |
    | **Red Arrow** | Money Flow Direction |
    | **Amount** | Decreases each hop (fees) |
endlegend

@enduml
